04121nam a22006135i 9781487516109DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20182018onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875161097 a10.3138/97814875161092doi  a(DE-B1597)501322  a(OCoLC)1040694495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0042002bisacsh04a338.409452231 aCottini, Luca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Art of Objects :bThe Birth of Italian Industrial Culture, 1878-1928 /cLuca Cottini. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. At the Origin of Italian Industrialism -- t2. Timepieces and Italian Modern Times -- t3. Industrial Photographs and the Fictional Vision -- t4. Bicycles and the Moving Body of the Nation -- t5. Gramophones, Radio, and the New Languages of Sound -- t6. Cigarettes and Smoke: The Modern Lightness of Being -- t7. Toys, Clothes, Furniture, and the Aesthetic Power of Play -- t8. The Industrial Laboratory of Italian Modernity -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Art of Objects is a cultural history of early Italian industrialism, set against the political, social, and intellectual background of post-unification Italy, and a cutting-edge investigation of the formation of Italy’s industrial culture at the turn of the 20th century. By adopting the unusual perspective of several objects of mass consumption, such as watches, photographs, bicycles, gramophones, cigarettes, and toys, author Luca Cottini examines their transformation from commercial items into aesthetic and philosophical icons. By focusing on the cultural significance of these objects, as they enter the market and appear in contemporary works of art and literature, The Art of Objects outlines a more comprehensive view of the age between the unification of Italy and Fascism, encompassing production and consumption, aesthetics and entrepreneurship, industry and the humanistic tradition. The observation of the slow formation of new languages, forms, practices, and experiences around these objects also provides an early documentation of the creative laboratory of Italy’s industrial culture. By reconstructing the origins of the Italian culture of design, the book ultimately investigates Italy’s critical reception of industrialism, the nation’s so-called “imperfect” modernization, and its ongoing quest for an original way to modernity.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751610940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487516109423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487516109.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK